Today, [[Shinto shrines]] in [[Chichibu region|Chichibu]], [[Saitama Prefecture]], continue to distribute [[ofuda]] featuring wolves, sustaining the faith<ref>[http://www9.plala.or.jp/sinsi/07sinsi/fukuda/ohkami/ohkami-07.html The wolf depicted on shrine ofuda]</ref>. Further south, atop [[Mount Mitake (Tokyo)|Mount Mitake]] in [[Tokyo]], {{ill|Musashi Mitake Shrine|ja|武蔵御嶽神社|12=draft|12=draft}} preserves a legend, based on 『{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft|12=draft}}』, about "Oinu-sama" ("Sacred Dog"). During the [[Eastern Expedition of Yamato Takeru|eastern expedition of Yamato Takeru]], an evil god appeared as a giant deer, which was defeated with [[wild garlic]] (nobiru). Subsequently, a white [[wolf]] emerged from nowhere to guide Yamato Takeru and his army safely, leading him to proclaim the wolf as "Ōkuchi no Makami," who would remain there as a protector. From the [[Edo period]]'s [[Tenpō]] era onward, Ōkuchi no Makami became revered for its power to repel theft and malevolent spirits. The shrine’s bronze komainu (guardian dogs) date back to 1807, while the bronze statue in front of the main hall was crafted by [[Seibo Kitamura]] in 1985<ref>[http://musashimitakejinja.jp/yuisho/oinusama/ The reverence for wolves as sacred beings at Musashi Mitake Shrine]</ref>.
