In [[Yamato Province]] (modern [[Nara Prefecture]]), the "Makami no Hara" (Makami Field) in [[Asuka, Nara|Asuka]] was home to an old wolf that devoured many people, leading to its deification because of its ferocity<ref>{{ill|Yamato Fudoki|ja|Yamato Province 風土記|qq=draft|qq=draft}} fragment (quoted in 『{{ill|Makurakotoba Shokumeishō|ja|枕詞燭明抄|qq=draft|qq=draft}}』), which describes a place name legend "Ōkuchi no Makami no Hara." 『{{ill|Manyoshu|ja|万葉集|qq=draft|qq=draft}}』 also refers to this area, indicating its recognition from the 8th century onward.</ref>. In 『{{ill|Manyoshu|ja|万葉集|qq=draft|qq=draft}}』, Volume 8, it is written: > "Ōkuchi no / Makami no Hara ni / Furu yuki wa / Itaku na furiso / Ie mo aranaku ni" > ("Snow falls deeply / Upon Ōkuchi Makami Field, / Yet do not let it fall so heavily, / For there are no homes here.") – [[Toneriko Daughter|舎人娘子]]
This area, later associated with the estate of [[Asuka Kinenoi|Asuka Kinunui no Mikoto no Oya Konoha]], became the site where [[Prince Umayado]] ([[Shotoku Taishi]]) reportedly began construction of [[Hōkōji]] (later {{ill|Asuka-dera|ja|飛鳥寺|qq=draft|qq=draft}}).
Today, [[Shinto shrines]] in [[Chichibu region|Chichibu]], [[Saitama Prefecture]], continue to distribute [[ofuda]] featuring wolves, sustaining the faith<ref>[http://www9.plala.or.jp/sinsi/07sinsi/fukuda/ohkami/ohkami-07.html The wolf depicted on shrine ofuda]</ref>. Further south, atop [[Mount Mitake (Tokyo)|Mount Mitake]] in [[Tokyo]], {{ill|Musashi Mitake Shrine|ja|武蔵御嶽神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} preserves a legend, based on 『{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|qq=draft}}』, about "Oinu-sama" ("Sacred Dog"). During the [[Eastern Expedition of Yamato Takeru|eastern expedition of Yamato Takeru]], an evil god appeared as a giant deer, which was defeated with [[wild garlic]] (nobiru). Subsequently, a white [[wolf]] emerged from nowhere to guide Yamato Takeru and his army safely, leading him to proclaim the wolf as "Ōkuchi no Makami," who would remain there as a protector. From the [[Edo period]]'s [[Tenpō]] era onward, Ōkuchi no Makami became revered for its power to repel theft and malevolent spirits. The shrine’s bronze komainu (guardian dogs) date back to 1807, while the bronze statue in front of the main hall was crafted by [[Seibo Kitamura]] in 1985<ref>[http://musashimitakejinja.jp/yuisho/oinusama/ The reverence for wolves as sacred beings at Musashi Mitake Shrine]</ref>.
